TI  - Insights into the prediction and driving factors of perfluorinated and polyfluoroalkyl substances in sediments from Taihu Lake of China using machine learning models
T2  - ENVIRONMENTAL POLLUTION
AB  - The spatiotemporal changes and environmental driving factors governing the distribution of perfluorinated and polyfluoroalkyl substances (PFAS) in the sediment cores of shallow lakes remain inadequately understood. This study investigated the occurrence and predicted future trends of PFAS in sediment cores from a shallow lake in China, and revealed the key influencing factors using time-series prediction and interpretable machine learning (IML) models. A decreasing trend of PFAS with depth in the three representative areas was found, with long-chain PFAS, such as perfluorooctanoic acid (PFOA) and perfluorooctane sulfonate (PFOS), predominating. The RQ of the top (0-4 cm) sediment cores indicated that they were in at a moderate ecological risk. Time-series forecasts using the Attention-CL model predicted increasing PFOA and PFOS concentrations from 2023 to 2034, suggesting potential consequences of delays in effective policy implementation. Feature importance and Shapley analyses revealed the importance of pH, total organic carbon (TOC), and oxidation-reduction potential (ORP) for PFAS. Partial dependence plots and individual conditional expectation showed the threshold effect of pH on PFOA and perfluoroundecanoic acid (PFUdA) to be 6.5, the threshold effect of ORP to be 200 mV, and the threshold effect of electrical conductivity to be 300 mu S/cm. The threshold effect of TOC on PFOA was 3.0 mg/g, whereas that on PFUdA was 3.5 mg/g. In general, the IML model highlights the importance of environmental parameters, such as pH, ORP, and TOC, in shaping PFAS distribution. These findings elucidate the complex interactions between sediment characteristics and PFAS distribution, informing targeted monitoring and remediation efforts in a broader environmental science field.
